04055nmm a2200577Ia 9780814724804DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147248047 a10.18574/nyu/9780814724804.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681069  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0870002bisacsh1 aRobbennolt, Jennifer K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Psychology of Tort Law /cValerie P. Hans, Jennifer K. Robbennolt. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPsychology and the Law ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Real World of Torts -- t2 Intentional Torts -- t3 Negligence -- t4 Causation -- t5 Limits on Liability: Duty and Scope of Liability -- t6 Damages -- t7 Defenses -- t8 Products Liability -- tConclusion: A Psychological Perspective on Tort Rules, Tort Cases, and Tort Reform -- tAppendix: Psychology and Torts -- tNotes -- tSubject Index -- tName Index -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTort law regulates most human activities: from driving a car to using consumer products to providing or receiving medical care. Injuries caused by dog bites, slips and falls, fender benders, bridge collapses, adverse reactions to a medication, bar fights, oil spills, and more all implicate the law of torts. The rules and procedures by which tort cases are resolved engage deeply-held intuitions about justice, causation, intentionality, and the obligations that we owe to one another. Tort rules and procedures also generate significant controversy-most visibly in political debates over tort reform.The Psychology of Tort Law explores tort law through the lens of psychological science. Drawing on a wealth of psychological research and their own experiences teaching and researching tort law, Jennifer K. Robbennolt and Valerie P. Hans examine the psychological assumptions that underlie doctrinal rules. They explore how tort law influences the behavior and decision-making of potential plaintiffs and defendants, examining how doctors and patients, drivers, manufacturers and purchasers of products, property owners, and others make decisions against the backdrop of tort law. They show how the judges and jurors who decide tort claims are influenced by psychological phenomena in deciding cases. And they reveal how plaintiffs, defendants, and their attorneys resolve tort disputes in the shadow of tort law. Robbennolt and Hans here shed fascinating light on the tort system, and on the psychological dynamics which undergird its functioning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Torts.2bisacsh1 aHans, Valerie P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814724804.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814724804423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814724804/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles